{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629635"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17290"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17290"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.21,0.1,0.14,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78755"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9980"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64104"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7227"},{"type":"tags","id":"7229"},{"type":"tags","id":"7322"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23378"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78755"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Radial","Ulnar","Medial pectoral","Musculocutaneous"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous\u003C/strong\u003E nerve arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus. It innervates the muscles responsible for elbow flexion, such as the biceps brachii, and provides sensation to the lateral aspect of the forearm. Damage to this nerve can result in weakness of elbow flexion and sensory loss in the lateral forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary\u003C/strong\u003E nerve arises from the posterior cord and innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles, it is also providing sensation to the skin over the deltoid region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial\u003C/strong\u003E nerve also arises from the posterior cord and is responsible for innervating the extensor muscles of the arm and forearm, as well as providing sensation to the posterior aspect of the arm and hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar\u003C/strong\u003E nerve arises from the medial cord and innervates the intrinsic muscles of the hand, providing sensation to the medial aspect of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial pectoral\u003C/strong\u003E nerve arises from the medial cord and innervates the pectoralis major and minor muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The musculocutaneous nerve arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus.","Understanding the anatomy of the brachial plexus is crucial for diagnosing and managing upper limb nerve injuries."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64104"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17290"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64104"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T16:30:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T16:34:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9980"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78755"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite